        "subject": {
          "reference": "urn:uuid:11111111-1111-4111-8111-111111111111"
        },
        "payload": [
          {
            "contentString": "{patientName} is a 33-year-old woman in the Czech Republic who comes in looking tired and uncomfortable, keeping the room dim because light worsens her headache symptoms with photophobia [SNOMED:G43.9]. She describes recurrent migraine attacks with headache, nausea, and occasional vomiting [SNOMED:G43.9]. During more severe episodes, the pain is often one-sided and throbbing, sometimes lasting from several hours to more than a day [MEDDIALOG:G43.9:2].\n\nShe works a desk-based administrative job and usually manages a busy weekday routine, but on headache days she struggles to look at screens or continue normal tasks because of the pain and light sensitivity [SNOMED:G43.9]. Outside work, she prefers quiet activities such as reading and short walks, and when a migraine starts she tends to withdraw to a dark room and limit social plans because of headache, nausea, and photophobia [SNOMED:G43.9].\n\n{patientName} lives with her partner and remains independent in daily activities between attacks. She has noticed that some attacks are severe enough to interrupt meals because of nausea and occasional vomiting [SNOMED:G43.9]. She is worried because the episodes have become disruptive to work and family life, although her physical and neurologic appearance between attacks is otherwise unremarkable, which is compatible with case descriptions of migraine assessment [PMID:38108544]."
          }
        ]
      }
    },
    {
      "fullUrl": "urn:uuid:4d2c4803-04e7-4460-8f9a-c5c2acffb46e",
      "resource": {
