                "code": "patient-history"
              }
            ]
          }
        ],
        "subject": {
          "reference": "urn:uuid:11111111-1111-4111-8111-111111111111"
        },
        "payload": [
          {
            "contentString": "{patientName} reports a history of recurrent migraine headaches with associated photophobia, nausea, and occasional vomiting [SNOMED:G43.9]. Her current pattern is episodic rather than continuous, with attacks that can last a few hours or extend beyond 24 hours [MEDDIALOG:G43.9:2]. She denies other major chronic neurologic disease by history, and there is no prior hospitalization documented for the headaches; this is a clinically plausible default not specified in the evidence.\n\nShe has not identified a single consistent trigger, but medication-related worsening is discussed in migraine literature, including reports that apixaban may increase migraine frequency or severity in susceptible patients [PMID:37582651]. She has no known history of refractory chronic migraine treatment, though nutraceutical prevention with L-carnitine has been discussed in the literature as a possible option in selected migraine patients, especially where energy deficiency or carnitine deficiency is considered [PMID:33755806].\n\nFamily history is notable for migraine in her mother, which is plausible given evidence that more common migraine variants often show familial aggregation and complex genetics [PMID:12720601]. Lifestyle is otherwise stable, and she tries to rest in a dark environment during attacks because light aggravates symptoms [SNOMED:G43.9]."
          }
        ]
      }
